PLN 105 million for companies in the video games industry from the National Centre for Research and Development
Nearly PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced the results of the third edition of the GameINN program on Friday.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by NCBR, among others, the development of a platform for field games based on the AR game engine that creates a map of the real world together with an application that allows users to transmit data; a test and training platform to verify practical skills on the workstation and professional improvement using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world with the use of the concept of industry 4.0 - is provided in the NCBR communication sent on Friday by PAP.
The goal of the sector-specific programme GameINN is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry in the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, today the Polish video game sector is growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 was 2.23 billion.
"The specially prepared research agenda GameINN and already reaching PLN 300 million support for entrepreneurs under this sector programme are an important impetus for the further dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev," we read in the Communication.
The video game industry is an excellent example of the effective exploitation of the potential we have in Poland.
"The government's incentives for innovative entrepreneurs, such as R &amp; D reliefs, competence improvement programmes, IP box and support programmes implemented by NCBR drive innovative businesses and allow them to compete more effectively in a highly competitive market," says Deputy Prime Minister Jarosław Gowin, Minister of Science and Higher Education, quoted in the Communication.
The head of the Ministry of Science notes that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of funding projects, but also stays in their pockets - three quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R &amp; D relief in 2018 than a year ago.
"The amount of deducted costs related to R &amp; D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in over PLN 300 million savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three GameINN editions," emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
Wojciech Kamieniecki, director of the NCBR, reminds us that in the previous two competitions funding with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million was awarded to 78 innovative projects.
The great interest in the third competition and the variety of proposals submitted show that the video gaming industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"In particular, it welcomes the fact that the selected projects - as in previous editions - include projects for not only entertainment but also industry-related 4.0 solutions," he adds.
In the third competition GameINN for funding up to PLN 20 million were able to apply for entrepreneurs, consortium of entrepreneurs and consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units.
The NCBR received 87 applications for the total amount of funding about PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million of funding.
Detailed information on the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sector programme is implemented under the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, including such companies as CD Project, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
