These trees can completely disappear from Europe
"42 per cent of tree species in Europe are at risk" warns the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) on Friday's "Red Book of European Trees."
The list includes chestnuts and hawks.
IUCN, an organisation based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes the list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was developed by specialists who, on the basis of research, concluded that of the 454 species of trees present in Europe (and elsewhere in the world) 42% are "highly at risk'.
Among the causes, the Red Paper mentions the rapid expansion of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most vulnerable are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
As far as typically European stands are concerned, according to experts from IUCN 58 percent of species are at risk, and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are threatened with extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Paper lists errors in the operation of the stand, accelerated urbanisation, too intense logging, followed by forest fires and changes in the European ecostytem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also at great risk.
"The aftermath of human activity leads to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and creates the risk of extinction of important and underestimated varieties in Europe, which form the basis of European ecosystems and have an impact on the health of our planet," concluded the report by Luc Bas, which runs the European IUCN office.
