GUS: Poland is getting better and better
According to a report published by the CSO on Friday on household budgets, as a good or rather good material situation was estimated by as many as 44 percent of them.
A year earlier, this percentage was 37.2 percent, 33.5 percent in 2016, and earlier, since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective household situation assessments, it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1 per cent of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2 per year earlier and over 20 per cent in 2009.
The best is the material situation of households of self-employed workers.
In this group, more than 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good.
At the second pole there are Rentist households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The number of children also has a significant impact on the subjective assessment of the household's material situation.
The worst is for single parents who raise their offspring, of whom 32 percent declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60%, and among childrenless households is 48.8%.
The effect of the 500+ programme is clearly visible in these statistics.
Before it was launched (in 2016) the worst of its material situation was assessed by single parents raising children and large families (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid growth of income, mainly from work.
However, that is not all, because the percentage of households that they consider to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of voivodships there is no clear correlation between income levels and the assessment of household material conditions.
The best grades are formulated by the inhabitants of the Opolskie Voivodship, where 48.9% of the respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
There are also Lubuskie Voivodships (47.7%), Śląskie (47.3%), Mazowieckie (47.3%), and Zachodniopomorskie (47.1%).
In Opole, however, the disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) was less than 94% of the national average in the previous year and 98% in Lubusek.
The highest income was the inhabitants of Mazowiecki (120 per cent of the national average) and Silesian (104 per cent).
On average in Poland the disposable income per person amounted to PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price changes) increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Against the background of previous years, it's a pretty low score.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7% and one year later by 6.3%.
Although revenue growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187 in the previous year, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased by 1.9% in real terms and by 4.3% in 2016 in real terms.
Household budget surveys suggest that the household currently spends 70.1 per cent of its disposable income, while in 2014 the share was above 80% and by 2006 exceeded 90%.
