Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion - such an extraordinary offer has been prepared for German visitors Görlitz.
Actions are designed to help combat the progressive decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Görlitz is the easternmost city of Germany.
A beautiful pastel town attracts 140 thousand tourists a year.
However, as "The Guardian" writes, the city is struggling with considerable problems.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city also struggles with a constant loss of population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which resulted in a 25% decrease in the population of the city.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000 people.
In order to fight the depopulation, officials came up with an idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been received.
Two thirds of them were made by the inhabitants of large cities.
Hungarian, Czech, United States and Great Britain were also interested in the programme.
"When we applied, we thought the program was supposed to convince people to move to Görlitz," said one of the project participants.
"Now we feel that it doesn't matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times the average across the country.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main objective of the programme is to obtain the opinion of the participants in the programme.
Information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move - what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to lure new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals for their life and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy or in the American Tulsa, Oklahoma.
